arch:property.oc:show_val: L22 is below L18 at the level of the bottom of a sounding cut at the NE corner of L18. The fill is compacted mudbrick like material. The locus was expanded to encompass the edge of a pit, L23 at the south baulk. We extended the locus again to the hard fill north of the pit until we came below a surface L29 and changed to L34. The interesting thing about this fill is that it is as hard as mudbrick and yet there are no brick lines or any indication of its construction. we found an area of large cobbles at the west baulk that had lots of obsidian beside them. The last week of digging we found an Ubaid pottery sherd beneath a cobble adjacent to the west baulk. We have found many Ubaid sherds mixed with late chalcolithic along with a lot of obsidian.
7/5YR 7/6 reddish yellow (clay lines), 10YR 6/2 light brownish grey fill
very compact clay loam with lines of clay and green clay
large animal bones, clay, green rock/clay, ash, burnt spots, pottery
very compacted fill against a pit, mudbrick like texture but no definable bricks, orange and green lines that are not brick but clay deposit

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
